FortyTwo BBS @VERSION@ - Build and Installation Status
======================================================

Development status
------------------

FortyTwo BBS is currently pre-alpha software intended exclusively for
development, code review and isolated testing.

There is currently no supported production installation procedure, public
deployment or supported upgrade path for existing MBSE BBS installations.

Do not expose the current software to public networks or use it on systems
containing valuable, personal, business-critical or irreplaceable data.

Use only an isolated test machine, disposable virtual machine or rootless
container. Maintain independent backups of all affected data and
configuration files.


Current platform target
-----------------------

The currently tested development environment is:

- x86_64 Linux
- glibc-based systems
- Ubuntu 25.10
- rootless Podman

A rootless Podman test image has been built and started successfully on the
development host.

Debian is planned as the first container deployment target, but is not yet a
supported platform.

BSD support is planned for later platform and build tests, but is not
currently supported or verified.


Legacy setup warning
--------------------

Do not run the inherited `SETUP.sh` script.

`SETUP.sh` still implements the historical MBSE BBS installation model. Among
other things, it creates the old `mbse` and `bbs` accounts, assumes
`/opt/mbse`, modifies system account files and configures legacy network
services.

Personal operating-system accounts for BBS users are not part of the intended
FortyTwo BBS architecture.

That procedure is being replaced and is not considered a supported
FortyTwo BBS installation method.


Source build status
-------------------

The source tree still uses parts of the inherited Autoconf and Make build
system.

A developer build generally requires:

- a C compiler such as GCC
- GNU Make
- a POSIX-compatible shell
- glibc development headers
- standard Linux and POSIX development interfaces

Optional functionality may use:

- zlib
- bzip2
- iconv
- GeoIP
- external archive programs
- external editors
- external virus scanners

The existing build system still contains technical compatibility names such
as `MBSE_ROOT`, `mbsebbs` and `mbsetup`. These internal names are being
reviewed gradually and do not represent the current product name.

The current `make install` target and privilege model are still under review.
They must not be treated as a safe or supported public installation method.

The normal build and installation path no longer includes `mbuseradd` or
`mbpasswd`. `mbtask` is installed without setuid or setgid bits.


Rootless Podman
---------------

The current rootless Podman test runtime uses fixed service accounts and
least-privilege permissions.

BBS users are intended to become internal application identities with stable,
opaque and server-generated user IDs. They are not intended to receive
personal Unix or container accounts.

The current Podman configuration remains a development setup and must not be
treated as a supported public deployment.


Telnet and SSH
--------------

Tested localhost-only Telnet and SSH configuration examples are available in:

`examples/fortytwo-access`

These examples are intended for isolated development testing.

SSH access starts only FortyTwo BBS through a forced command. Command
execution, forwarding, tunnelling, SCP and SFTP are disabled.

Public new-user registration remains disabled until registration,
authentication and session handling have been migrated completely to the
internal BBS identity system.


Web access
----------

FortyTwo BBS can generate static HTML indexes for file areas, including
download links and optional image previews.

FortyTwo BBS does not include its own HTTP server. A separate web server or
web-server container is required to publish these files.

Generated content should be mounted read-only wherever practical and must not
expose credentials, private messages or internal BBS data.


